==English==

===Etymology===
From {{etyl|xno}} {{term|novice|lang=xno}}, {{etyl|frm}} {{term|novice|lang=fr}}, from {{etyl|la}} {{term|lang=la|novicius|novīcius}}, later {{term|lang=la|novitius||new, newly arrived}} (in Late Latin as a noun, {{term|lang=la|novicius}}, masculine, {{term|lang=la|novicia||feminine, one who has newly entered a monastery or a convent}}), from {{term|lang=la|novus||new}}.

===Pronunciation===
* {{a|UK}} {{IPA|/ˈnɒvɪs/}}

===Noun===
{{en-noun}}

# A [[beginner]]; one who is not very [[familiar]] or [[experienced]] in a particular subject. {{defdate|from 14th c.}}
#: ''I'm only a '''novice''' at coding, and my programs frequently have bugs that more experienced programmers wouldn't make.''
# {{religion}} A [[new]] [[member]] of a [[religious]] [[order]] accepted on a [[conditional]] basis, prior to [[confirmation]]. {{defdate|from 14th c.}}
#* '''1983''', {{w|Lawrence Durrell}}, ''Sebastian'', Faber & Faber 2004 (''Avignon Quintet''), p. 1137:
#*: Nor had it been difficult to find a Coptic priest who, together with his youthful '''novice''', chanted the seemingly interminable Egyptian service of the dead [...].

